JAPANESE ENCEPHALITIS - AUSTRALIA (26): NEW SOUTH WALES) FATALITY
*****************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Tue 24 2022 3:04 PM AEST
Source: Sky News [edited]
https://www.skynews.com.au/australia-news/nsw-man-david-kiefel-dies-after-three-month-battle-with-rare-mosquitoborne-virus-japanese-encephalitis/news-story/afec0fe87086de0ea43dd4ba27ed3cee


A 61-year-old man from regional New South Wales has become the 5th person in Australia to die from the rare mosquito-borne virus Japanese encephalitis.

[DK] from Corowa died at Albury Base Hospital on 20 May [2022] after contracting the virus on the New South Wales-Victorian border in mid-February [2022].

DK had been placed on life support after developing a severe form of the virus [infection].

His wife, who spent almost every day by his bedside, confirmed her husband's passing.

"Without possibility of life quality, DK chose palliation to journey to heaven on his own terms," his wife told The Border Mail. "Such courage and dignity; a mark of the much-loved man in our Corowa community."

An outpouring of tributes have flowed from the Corowa community.

To date 37 people have been infected by Japanese encephalitis across Australia, with New South Wales accounting for 13 cases.

Japanese encephalitis virus is spread to humans and other animals through bites from infected mosquitoes.

Although those who are bitten by the mosquito rarely develop symptoms, those who do have a 30 per cent chance of dying, according to the World Health Organization.

Symptoms can include severe neurological illness with headache, convulsions and reduced consciousness in some cases.

[Byline: Miriah Davis]

