Communicated by:
ProMED from HealthMap Alerts

[Fatalities due to Japanese encephalitis (JE) virus infection in Australia this year (2022) have been very few. Unfortunately, the case above is one of them, after a prolonged illness. Most JE virus infections are asymptomatic or mild febrile cases. As the weather becomes cooler and vector mosquitoes less active, transmission of JE virus is expected to decline, as apparently is the situation. The open question now is if JEV will become established in any or all of the 4 affected states. Ongoing surveillance of piggeries and mosquitoes should provide evidence of the continuing presence of the virus in the 4 states. Providing adequate surveillance over the very large geographic 4-state area of the outbreak will be a challenge for surveillance efforts. One hopes that the virus will disappear in the affected area and transmission will cease permanently. We shall see if it does. - Mod.TY

